      • transform

        public static <T,V> BucketSelector<V> transform​(BucketSelector<T> input,
                                                Converter<V,T> transformer)
        Wrap a BucketSelector that handles one value type inside one that handles a different value type, using a Converter that converts individual values from one type to the other.
        Type Parameters:
        T - The value type of the existing input BucketSelector.
        V - The value type of the BucketSelector that this method will return.
        Parameters:
        input - The existing BucketSelector instance, which handles value type T. This is encapsulated inside a returned BucketSelector that handles value type V.
        transformer - A Converter that can change values of type T into V and values of type V into T.
        Returns:
        A BucketSelector that can handle the value type V.

      • powerOf2LongValues

        public static BucketSelector<Long> powerOf2LongValues​(int minPower,
                                                      int numBuckets)
        Get a BucketSelector that has upper bound values that are consecutive whole-number powers of 2.

        Example: arguments minPower=2 and numBuckets=5 would generate upper bound values 4, 8, 16, and 32.

        Parameters:
        minPower - The smallest power of 2 to use when generating upper bound values.
        numBuckets - The number of buckets that the BucketSelector should provide.
        Returns:
        A BucketSelector<Long> instance.

      • exponential

        public static BucketSelector<Double> exponential​(double base,
                                                 double minPower,
                                                 int numBuckets)
        Get a BucketSelector that has upper bound values that are double values that are part of an exponential series. Each bucket value's exponent is 1.0 plus the exponent of the previous bucket value.

        Example: arguments base=5.0, minPower=0.0, and numBuckets=5 would generate base and exponent values of 50, 51, 52, and 53, so the upper bound values would be 1.0, 5.0, 25.0, and 125.0.

        Parameters:
        base - The base that will be raised to the specified exponents to generate upper bound values.
        minPower - The smallest exponent to use when generating upper bound values.
        numBuckets - The number of buckets into which values should be counted.
        Returns:
        A BucketSelector<Double> instance.

      • linearLongValues

        public static BucketSelector<Long> linearLongValues​(long lowestUpperBound,
                                                    long highestUpperBound,
                                                    int numBuckets)
        Get a BucketSelector that has upper bound values that are evenly distributed between a smallest and largest value.

        Example: arguments lowestUpperBound=0, highestUpperBound=20, and numBuckets=6 would generate upper bound values 0, 5, 10, 15, and 20.

        Parameters:
        lowestUpperBound - The upper-bound value for the first bucket (index 0).
        highestUpperBound - The upper-bound value for the next-to-last bucket (index (numBuckets - 2)).
        numBuckets - The total number of buckets.
        Returns:
        A BucketSelector<Long> instance.
